Theories of Uncertainty¶

  • Probability theory
    • What are the elements of probability theory?
      • Random experiment (an idealized chance mechanism)
      • The goal is to predict results of a random experiment
  • Statistical theory
    • What are the elements of statistical theory?
      • Dataset (a set of observations)
      • The goal is to propose a model (random experiment) that could have given rise to the dataset

Random Experiment¶

As a conceptual model of a simple chance mechanism, a random experiment consists of

  1. Purpose
    • What is the context? (configuration, environment, setup)
      • resistance of this resistor (in my hand) vs.
      • resistance of a resister of this batch
    • What are you looking for? (list of possible outcomes to watch)
      • resistance only (dc analysis)
      • resistance and reactance (high frequencies)
  2. Procedure
    • an unambiguous sequence of actions (clearly specified)
    • not open for individual interpretation (deterministic)
  3. Execution
    • Someone (or robot) carries out the prescribed procedure in the prescribed setup
    • this is where you may face some uncontrollable and unpredictable influences
      • in the absence of this you have a deterministic experiment
        • how many departments in NUCES?
        • how many departments in an unspecified university
    • a single execution (also called a trial) is implied in the definition
      • if multiple trials are needed, change the (specified) procedure (and hence the definition)
  4. Noting
    • The possible outcomes of interest are noted (assumed deterministic)
    • What is noted here is an actual outcome
    • Any constraints (natural or deliberate) in the specified setup will limit what can be noted
    • outcomes (specified in the statement of purpose) may be too detailed for some problems
      • results of interest (called events) hide the finer details for convenience

An example is needed to illustrate the definition above.

  1. Purpose

From Concepts to Math¶

Examples (Make appropriate assumptions in each case)¶

  1. Toss a coin and note the outcome. What are the possible outcomes?

    S={T,H}S={T,H}

  2. Toss a coin twice and note the outcome.
    • What are the possible outcomes?

      S={TT,TH,HT,HH}S={TT,TH,HT,HH}

    • What could be events of your interest?
      • Say, you are interested in the number of heads, then typical events are

        "no head" ↔A0={TT}↔A0={TT}
        "one head" ↔A1={TH,HT}↔A1={TH,HT}
        "two heads" ↔A2={HH}↔A2={HH}

  3. Toss a coin three times and note the outcome.
    • What are the possible outcomes?

      S={TTT,TTH,THT,THH,HTT,HTH,HHT,HHH}S={TTT,TTH,THT,THH,HTT,HTH,HHT,HHH}

    • What could be events of your interest?
    • Say, you are interested in the number of tails, then typical events are

      "no tail" ↔B0={HHH}↔B0={HHH}
      "one tail" ↔B1={THH,HTH,HHT}↔B1={THH,HTH,HHT}
      "two tails" ↔B2={TTH,THT,HTT}↔B2={TTH,THT,HTT}
      "three tails" ↔B3={TTT}↔B3={TTT}

  4. Toss a coin until the first head occurs.
    • What are the possible outcomes?

      S={H,TH,TTH,TTTH,⋯}S={H,TH,TTH,TTTH,⋯}

    • What could be events of your interest?
    • Say, you are interested in the number of trials needed for the first head, then typical events are

      "no trial" ↔C0=∅↔C0=∅
      "one trial" ↔C1={H}↔C1={H}
      "two trials" ↔C2={TH}↔C2={TH}
      "three trials" ↔C3={TTH}↔C3={TTH}

  5. Toss a coin until the first head occurs and count the number of tosses.

    S=N={1,2,3,⋯}S=N={1,2,3,⋯} as the statement contains "count"

  6. A hacker is repeatedly and persistently trying to break into a company’s computer server. Count the number of attempts needed for a successful break-in.

    S=NS=N

  7. Count the number of clicks on a Facebook post in an hour.

    S={0}∪NS={0}∪N
    This is a simpler set than the one with the largest element that cannot be determined.

  8. Measure the lifetime of a light bulb in a typical home environment.

    S={x∈R:x≥0}S={x∈R:x≥0}
    This is a simpler set than the one with the largest element that cannot be determined.

The Meaning of "Random"¶

  • The uncontrollable and unpredictable influences make it impossible to predict the outcome of a single trial
    • A random mechanism is assumed to underlie the influences
  • The experiment can be repeated under identical conditions
    • The random mechanism does not change from trial to trial
    • this is an assumption and cannot be guarranteed to hold in practice
      • give a few obvious examples
    • discernible regularities exist in the frequency of occurrence associated with different outcomes
      • this needs to be made precise mathematically, but you are not ready for that

Properties of Relative Frequency of an Event¶

A random experiment is repeated nn times. The occurrence pattern of an event AA can be described with the help of quantities defined in the following.

  • Absolute frequency an(A)an(A) is the number of occurrences of AA in the nn trials.

  • Properties of absolute frequency

    1. 0≤an(A)≤n0≤an(A)≤n

    2. an(S)=nan(S)=n

    3. an(∅)=0an(∅)=0

    4. For disjoint events AA and BB,

      an(A∪B)=an(A)+an(B)an(A∪B)=an(A)+an(B)

    5. For pairwise disjoint events A1,A2,…,AmA1,A2,…,Am

      an(⋃i=1mAi)=∑i=1man(Ai)an(⋃i=1mAi)=∑i=1man(Ai)

  • Relative frequency

    rn(A)=an(A)nrn(A)=an(A)n

  • Properties of relative frequency

    1. 0≤rn(A)≤10≤rn(A)≤1

    2. rn(S)=1rn(S)=1

    3. rn(∅)=0rn(∅)=0

    4. For disjoint events AA and BB,

      rn(A∪B)=rn(A)+rn(B)rn(A∪B)=rn(A)+rn(B)

    5. For pairwise disjoint events A1,A2,…,AmA1,A2,…,Am

      rn(⋃i=1mAi)=∑i=1mrn(Ai)rn(⋃i=1mAi)=∑i=1mrn(Ai)

  • Interpretation of relative frequency

    • The binary occurence of AA in trial ii can be defined by

      bi(A)={10A occurs in trial iA does not occur in trial ibi(A)={1A occurs in trial i0A does not occur in trial i

    • then the absolute frequency can be expressed as the sum

      an(A)=∑i=1nbi(A)an(A)=∑i=1nbi(A)

    • and the relative frequency as the arithmetic mean

      rn(A)=an(A)n=1n∑i=1nbi(A)=b¯nrn(A)=an(A)n=1n∑i=1nbi(A)=b¯n

    • the relative frequency of an event is, in fact, its average occurrence per trial

Long-run Relative Frequency¶

Statistical Regularity The event AA is said to exhibit statistical regularity if the long-run relative frequency converges to what is called the frequentist probability of AA :
P(A)=limn→∞rn(A)P(A)=limn→∞rn(A)
